12 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
13 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
14 Article – Commercial Law
15 13–301.
16 Unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade practices include any:
17 (14) Violation of a provision of:
18 (xliv) Title 14, Subtitle 49 of this article; [or]
19 (xlv) Section 12–6C–09.1 of the Health Occupations Article; or
20 (XLVI) SECTION 5–428 OF THE COURTS ARTICLE; OR
21 Article – Courts and Judicial Proceedings
22 5–428.
23 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “CONSUMER CONTRACT” MEANS A CONTRACT
24 INVOLVING THE SALE, LEASE, OR PROVISION OF GOODS OR SERVICES THAT ARE FOR
25 PERSONAL, FAMILY, OR HOUSEHOLD PURPOSES.
26 (B) ANY PROVISION IN A CONSUMER CONTRACT THAT SETS A SHORTER
27 PERIOD OF TIME TO BRING AN ACTION UNDER OR ON THE CONSUMER CONTRACT
28 THAN REQUIRED UNDER THE LAW OF THE STATE AT THE TIME THE CONSUMER
29 CONTRACT IS ISSUED OR DELIVERED IS AGAINST PUBLIC POLICY AND VOID.
30 (C) IF A CONSUMER CONTRACT CONTAINS A PROVISION THAT IS ILLEGAL
31 UNDER THIS SECTION:

HOUSE BILL 431 3
1 (1) A COURT MAY NOT GIVE EFFECT TO THE PROVISION; AND
2 (2) A DEFENSE TO LIABILITY UNDER THE CONSUMER CONTRACT MAY
3 NOT BE BASED ON THE SHORTER LIMITATION PERIOD.
4 (D) A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION IS:
5 (1) AN UNFAIR, ABUSIVE, OR DECEPTIVE TRADE PRACTICE WITHIN
6 THE MEANING OF TITLE 13 OF THE COMMERCIAL LAW ARTICLE; AND
7 (2) SUBJECT TO THE ENFORCEMENT AND PENALTY PROVISIONS
8 CONTAINED IN TITLE 13 OF THE COMMERCIAL LAW ARTICLE, EXCEPT § 13–411 OF
9 THE COMMERCIAL LAW ARTICLE.
10 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall be construed to
11 apply only prospectively and may not be applied or interpreted to have any effect on or
12 application to any contract entered into before the effective date of this Act.
13 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
14 October 1, 2025.
